      <comment>[[Help:Reverting|Reverted]] edits by [[Special:Contributions/219.89.245.97|219.89.245.97]] ([[User talk:219.89.245.97|talk]]) to last version by Colonies Chris</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{wiktionary}}
'''''Alfonso''''' (Italian and Spanish), '''''Alfons''''' ([[Catalan language|Catalan]], Dutch, German and Polish), '''''Afonso''''' (Portuguese and [[Galician language|Galician]]), '''''Affonso''''' (Ancient Portuguese), '''''[[Alphonse]]''''', '''''Alfonse''''' (Italian, French and English), '''''Αλφόνσος''''' ('''Alfonsos''', '''Alphonsos''') (Greek), '''''Alphonsus''''' (Latin), '''''Alphons''''' (Dutch), '''''Alfonsu''''' in ([[Leonese language|Leonese]]) or '''''Alphonso''''' (English and [[Filipino language|Filipino]]) is a masculine name, originally from the [[Gothic language]], '''''Alfonsas''''' (Lithuanian).

The original meaning of the name is uncertain. It could be derived from ''adal'' &quot;noble&quot; and ''funs'' &quot;ready&quot; or from the name '''''Hildefuns''''', which is preserved in the Spanish and Portuguese '''''Ildefonso''''' ([[Latinisation (literature)|Latinised]] as ''Ildephonsus'') and means &quot;battle ready&quot; (''hild'' &quot;battle&quot; combined with ''funs'' &quot;ready&quot;). In any case is almost certainly of Germanic and not of Latin origin.

It is the name of many historical personages and others:
{{TOC right}}

