  <page>
    <title>Autpert Ambrose</title>
    <id>1714</id>
    <revision>
      <id>427716297</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-06T08:38:13Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>PBS-AWB</username>
        <id>11989454</id>
      </contributor>
      <comment>/* External links */AWB general  fixes and, replaced: {{1913CE → {{Catholic Encyclopedia poster using [[Project:AWB|AWB]]</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Autpert Ambrose (Ambroise)''' ({{lang-la|'''Ambrosius Autpertus'''}}) (ca. 730 – 784) was a [[Franks|Frankish]] [[Benedictine]] monk.

He became abbot of San Vicenzo on the Volturno in South Italy in the time of [[Desiderius]], king of the [[Lombards]].  Autpert's election as [[abbot]] caused internal dissent at St. Vicenzo, and both [[Pope Stephen III]] and [[Charlemagne]] intervened.  The disagreement was based both on objections to Autpert's personality and to his Frankish origin.

He wrote a considerable number of works on the Bible and religious subjects generally. Among these are commentaries on the [[Apocalypse]], on the [[Psalms]], and on the [[Song of Solomon]]; ''Lives of Saints Paldo, Tuto and Vaso''; ''[[Assumption of Mary|Assumption]] of the Virgin''; and a ''Combat between the Virtues and the Vices''.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Ambrose, Autpert}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2009, Pope [[Benedict XVI]] gave a homily about him in Saint Peter's square. In this homily, Autpert's death date is given as 784 (older scholarship had given a date between 778 and 779).&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.zenit.org/article-25689?l=english On Ambrose Autpert, &quot;1st Mariologist of the West&quot;]&lt;/ref&gt;

