'''Apollo 7''' (October 11–22, 1968) was the first manned mission in the [[United States|American]] [[Apollo program|Apollo space program]], and the first manned [[United States|US]] space flight after a cabin fire killed the crew of what was to have been the first manned mission, AS-204 (later renamed [[Apollo 1]]), during a launch pad test in 1967. It was a [[List of Apollo mission types|C type mission]]—an 11-day Earth-orbital mission, the first manned launch of the [[Saturn IB]] launch vehicle, and the first three-person US space mission. The crew was commanded by [[Wally Schirra|Walter M. Schirra]], with Command Module Pilot [[Donn F. Eisele]], and Lunar Module Pilot [[Walter Cunningham|R. Walter Cunningham]].

The mission was the first manned test of the redesigned Block II [[Apollo Command/Service Module]]. It flew in Earth orbit so the crew could check life-support, propulsion, and control systems.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.upi.com/Audio/Year_in_Review/Events-of-1968/N.-Korea-Seize-U.S.-Ship/12303153093431-9/#title 1968 in Space; 1968 Year in Review], UPI.com&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; Despite tension between the crew and ground controllers, the mission was a technical success, which gave NASA the confidence to launch [[Apollo 8]] around the Moon  two months later. However, the flight would prove to be the last space flight for all of its three crew members. It was also the final manned launch from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station]], Florida.

==Crew==
{{Spaceflight crew
|terminology      = Astronaut
|position1        = Commander
|crew1_up         = [[Wally Schirra|Walter M. Schirra]]
|flights1_up      = Third and last
|position2        = Command Module Pilot
|crew2_up         = [[Donn F. Eisele]]
|flights2_up      = Only
|position3        = Lunar Module Pilot
|crew3_up         = [[Walter Cunningham|R. Walter Cunningham]]
|flights3_up      = Only
|notes            = This crew was originally slated to fly a second Block I mission after [[Apollo 1]]. They then became the backup crew for Apollo 1 after this second mission was cancelled.&lt;br&gt;
'''Lunar Module Pilot''' was the official title used for the third pilot position in Block II missions, regardless of whether the [[Apollo Lunar Module|LM]] spacecraft was present or not. The LMP performed the duties of [[flight engineer]], monitoring the systems of both the [[Apollo Command/Service Module|CSM]] and LM spacecraft.
}}

